<prompt>
  <objective>
    Fix WebSocket connection drops that cause missed lever press events during
    active REACHER neuroscience experiment sessions. The backend on a Raspberry Pi
    always records events in kernel.behavior_data[], but when the WebSocket drops
    and reconnects, the frontend never fetches the missed events. Add event
    recovery on reconnect and relax ping/pong timeouts.
  </objective>

  <context>
    <architecture>
      The event pipeline flows:
        Arduino serial → kernel read_serial() thread → serial queue (max 5000)
        → handle_queue() thread → update_behavioral_events() → behavior_data[]
        → _emit("event", entry) → event_callback → enqueue_event()
        → WebSocket queue (max 10000) → _broadcast_worker() → ws.send_text()
        → frontend ReacherWebSocket.onmessage → handleMessage() → pushEvent()
        → Zustand store behaviorData[]

      Loss point: When no WebSocket client is connected, the broadcast worker
      drains the queue but sends to an empty connection set. Events are silently
      discarded from the WebSocket layer. However, the kernel's behavior_data[]
      retains them — the backend is always authoritative.

      Existing recovery API: GET /api/data/{session_id}/behavior?since=N returns
      behavior_data[N:] and a "total" field with the full list length. The
      frontend client already has getBehavior(id, since?) but never calls it
      after reconnection.

      Note: The kernel emits ALL behavioral events via WebSocket (including
      PAVLOV device events), but behavior_data[] excludes PAVLOV events and
      events when not program_running. The frontend pushEvent() also gates on
      state === "running" but does NOT filter PAVLOV. This indexing mismatch
      means we use full-replace recovery (fetch all events from backend,
      replace frontend state) rather than incremental since=N for correctness
      across all paradigms.
    </architecture>

